      "focuses": [
        "Convert built strength into court-relevant power — rotational, reactive, and unilateral.",
        "Reinforce shoulder girdle resilience under higher velocity demands."
      ],
      "message": {
        "paragraphs": [
          "Mehraneh, the first ten weeks were about building something worth using. You did that — the squat went from 10 kilograms to 50 while your knees stayed quiet. The shoulder that was a 6 out of 10 in Week 1 hasn't been mentioned since Week 2. The foundation is real. This cycle is where it becomes athletic.",
          "Power Transfer has one job: take the strength you built and teach your body to express it fast. The med-ball throws, the box jumps, the speed pulls — these aren't harder versions of what you've been doing. They're a different quality altogether. The shift you need to make mentally is from pushing hard to moving fast. Every repetition of every power exercise has one cue that overrides all others: intent. A slow throw is a wasted rep.",
          "By the end of these five weeks, you will feel a difference on the court before you see one in the gym. First steps, change of direction, the moment you load a forehand — these are the outputs. The gym work is the input."
        ],
        "outcomes": [
          "Reactive jump landings controlled and pain-free under load",
          "Rotational throw velocity visibly faster side to side",
          "Squat at 5 reps heavy — moved with intent, not grind",
          "Landmine push press progressed past the 5 kg OHP wall",
          "Trap-bar speed pulls feeling explosive, not effortful",
          "Day 4 completed every week without exception"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "num": 4,
      "name": "Performance Peak",
      "tagline": "Sharpen the Weapon",
      "weeks": "Weeks 16–20",
      "startDate": "2026-07-21",
      "endDate": "2026-08-24",
      "focuses": [
        "Sharpen athletic output — speed, reactive strength, and sport-specific conditioning.",
        "Sustain structural integrity under competition load; refine movement economy."
      ],
      "teaser": {
        "paragraphs": [
          "Cycle 4 is where everything this block produced gets put in front of an opponent. The speed gets tested. The reactions get tested. The engine gets pushed to its ceiling and asked to sustain it.",
          "There are no more base-building phases after this. What you bring into Cycle 4 is what you play with.",
          "Earn it in these five weeks."
        ]
      }
    },
