  "notes": {
    "greeting": "For You, Mehraneh",
    "cards": [
      {
        "icon": "⚡",
        "title": "Power Training Feels Different — That's the Point",
        "body": "Everything you've done until now has been about generating force under control — slow eccentrics, tempo, grinding through reps. Power training inverts that. The stimulus is speed of movement, not load or duration. A med-ball throw that takes two seconds is half as effective as one that takes one. Your body will feel the difference within the first session — lighter loads, longer rests, fewer reps, but every rep done at maximum intent. Don't mistake the lower numbers for easier work. It's a different kind of hard."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🦵",
        "title": "Your Knees Are Cleared — Own It",
        "body": "Bilateral knee pain was 5 out of 10 in your first session. You haven't mentioned your knees since Week 2. That clearance has a consequence: this cycle reintroduces reactive work — pogo jumps, lateral bounds, box jumps — that was pulled from the program specifically because of your knees. Land every jump soft and quiet; the sound of a landing tells you everything about how the force was absorbed. If anything above a dull ache (3 out of 10) appears, stop the reactive block and move to the strength exercises. But you've earned the right to jump again."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🛡️",
        "title": "The Shoulder Under Velocity — A New Test",
        "body": "Your shoulder resolved through the last cycle — the integrity block worked. This cycle introduces a new challenge: velocity-based pressing through the landmine. The angle is shoulder-friendly (diagonal, not vertical), and the leg drive takes the grinding pressure off the joint. What to watch: any pinching or catching sensation at the top of the press means the load or angle needs adjusting — not pushing through. The three integrity exercises (external rotation, Y-T-W, face pull) stay exactly as they are. They are the reason your shoulder is healthy. Don't skip them on hard days."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🧠",
        "title": "The Autoregulation Protocol",
        "body": "When life is heavy, the limiter is mental and timing, not your body — you said so yourself. So this cycle has a built-in rule: if your readiness is poor (bad sleep, high stress), drop every RPE target by one point and skip the last accessory. The minimum effective dose for any session is the first power exercise and the first primary lift. Do those, and the session counts. If you can only train once this week, train Day 3. This isn't permission to slack — it's engineering for a life that doesn't always cooperate."
      },
      {
        "icon": "😴",
        "title": "Sleep Is Training",
        "body": "Your sleep runs 2 a.m. to 11:30 a.m. That's not a problem of quantity — it's a delayed rhythm. The Zone 2 session on Day 4 is one of the most effective interventions for resetting this pattern over time; done consistently, it shifts the curve. What you can control immediately: avoid screens and high-stimulus content in the 30 minutes before bed, and keep the sleep onset time as consistent as possible even on days off. On days when sleep was poor the night before, the autoregulation protocol kicks in — lower RPE, lighter day. A low-quality training day after broken sleep costs more than it returns."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🎾",
        "title": "The Throws Are Your Forehand",
        "body": "The medicine ball rotational throw with a step is not a gym exercise that happens to look like tennis. It is the exact neuromuscular pattern of a forehand and backhand — ground force, hip rotation, trailing arm, follow-through. Every rep at maximum intent is a rep of sport-specific power development. The reason we added the step this cycle is that footwork precedes every shot you hit. Load the back hip first. The arms are the last thing to move. If you've ever felt your shots come from your arm instead of your whole body, this is where that changes."
      }
    ]
  }
